column10:
His Reply: unfortunately would not be an interesting opportunity for us. The main reasons are that the doses used in the animal experiments are very high (900mg/kg) and that the time when you do the IGTT is only after 50 days. In addition you reported only an effect to blood glucose.

In our assessment it would be necessary to have a much more potent drug acting at a lower dose and with a faster on-set of action. In addition an effect in an IGTT is good but it would be more important to demonstrate good HbA1c lowering in a Diabetes animal model. Also it would be important for us to see additional benefits like a good weight reduction potential, or beneficial effects on cardiovascular parameters to be interesting for us.

column10:
Alex was very kind to give a very thorough analysis: Thank you very much for sending these materials over. Having reviewed them, they are not suitable for investment by Syncona:

* Prof. Eshhar’s work is interesting but his use of sphingolimod to trap T cells in lymphatics seems challenging from the perspective of product ownership, and there is no development programme; it could be a suitable project for an existing allogeneic CAR-T company to explore.
* Prof. Geiger’s and Prof. Friedman’s expansion method is also good but similarly, in the absence of any development programme, it represents a potential piece of IP for a T cell therapy manufacturer rather than an actual investment thesis for a company.
